12/12 For observers, look at the scoreboard when the final siren sounds. In the mean time try to filter out the pre-game chatter.
11/12 There is noise from VCs saying they can pick the next unicorn and they are a new paradigm in alpha generation.
10/12 There is noise from startups about being a moonshot and not being able to find funding
9/12 Meanwhile the investor, if picking winners, must believe they are in the top 5% of investors capable of generating meaningful returns
8/12 When a startup talks capital raise with an investor the entrepreneur believes they are in the 0.5% of ventures that will succeed
7/12 However, even in the US, VC returns mirror the risk profile of startups => 90% of returns are generated by the top 5-10% of VCs
6/12 If most investors were capable of picking winners (especially at early stage) there would be normal/bell curve distribution of returns
5/12 But in fairness, the results/returns are as asymmetrically skewed on the investor side as they are on the startup side
4/12 The ongoing dialogue about lack of funding for startups in Australia is skewed by the 90-95% of startups that are uninvestable
3/12 Good entrepreneurs get funded & find a way for their startup to succeed. They bootstrap &/or are funded by local or global investors
2/12 Only ~50 or 0.5% have a meaningful exit - trade sale (mainly) or IPO. ~9,500 startups are not funded or can’t get follow-on funding
1/12 Over 5yrs ~10,000 startups form in Australia. Of these, ~1,000 receive seed funding & ~400 receive angel stage/follow-on funding
